The transformation template
A useful general template is:
g(x) = a*f(b*(x - h)) + k
where:

a vertically stretches/compresses and may reflect across the x-axis;
b horizontally compresses/stretches and may reflect across the y-axis;
h shifts the graph horizontally;
k shifts the graph vertically.







WarningHorizontal transformations feel backward



The expression f(x - 3) shifts the graph right by 3, not left. The input must be 3 units larger before the base function sees the same internal value.

Reading the picture
In the plot:

the black segment is the radius of the unit circle;
the red segment shows the cosine component;
the blue segment shows the sine component.

Because every point is on a circle of radius 1, sine and cosine always stay between -1 and 1.

Interactive unit circle
Use the slider or type an angle between -360 and 360 degrees. Positive angles rotate counterclockwise; negative angles rotate clockwise.

unitCircleExplorer()







function unitCircleExplorer() {
  const root = html`&lt;section class="trig-explorer"&gt;&lt;/section&gt;`;
  const slider = html`&lt;input class="trig-angle-slider" type="range" min="-360" max="360" step="1" value="45"&gt;`;
  const input = html`&lt;input class="trig-angle-input" type="number" min="-360" max="360" step="1" value="45"&gt;`;
  const chart = html`&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;`;
  const values = html`&lt;div class="trig-values"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;`;

  const controls = html`&lt;div class="trig-controls"&gt;
    &lt;label&gt;
      &lt;span&gt;Angle&lt;/span&gt;
      ${slider}
    &lt;/label&gt;
    &lt;label&gt;
      &lt;span&gt;Degrees&lt;/span&gt;
      ${input}
    &lt;/label&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;`;

  slider.addEventListener("input", () =&gt; {
    input.value = slider.value;
    render();
  });

  input.addEventListener("input", () =&gt; {
    const angle = clamp(Number(input.value) || 0, -360, 360);
    input.value = angle;
    slider.value = angle;
    render();
  });

  root.append(controls, chart, values);
  render();
  return root;

  function render() {
    const angle = Number(slider.value);
    chart.innerHTML = "";
    chart.append(drawUnitCircle(angle));

    const radians = angle * Math.PI / 180;
    const cosine = Math.cos(radians);
    const sine = Math.sin(radians);

    values.innerHTML = `
      &lt;span&gt;cos(${angle}°) = ${cosine.toFixed(3)}&lt;/span&gt;
      &lt;span&gt;sin(${angle}°) = ${sine.toFixed(3)}&lt;/span&gt;
    `;
  }
}







function drawUnitCircle(angleDegrees) {
  const width = 560;
  const height = 560;
  const margin = 44;
  const radius = 210;
  const center = { x: width / 2, y: height / 2 };
  const radians = angleDegrees * Math.PI / 180;
  const point = {
    x: center.x + radius * Math.cos(radians),
    y: center.y - radius * Math.sin(radians)
  };
  const projection = { x: point.x, y: center.y };
  const radiusLabel = {
    x: (center.x + point.x) / 2 + 10,
    y: (center.y + point.y) / 2 - 10
  };
  const cosineLabel = {
    x: (center.x + projection.x) / 2,
    y: center.y + 28
  };
  const sineLabel = {
    x: projection.x + (projection.x &gt;= center.x ? 12 : -12),
    y: (projection.y + point.y) / 2
  };

  const svg = d3.create("svg")
    .attr("viewBox", [0, 0, width, height])
    .attr("role", "img")
    .attr("aria-label", "Interactive unit circle showing sine and cosine")
    .attr("class", "trig-unit-circle");

  svg.append("circle")
    .attr("cx", center.x)
    .attr("cy", center.y)
    .attr("r", radius)
    .attr("fill", "none")
    .attr("stroke", "#9aa0a6")
    .attr("stroke-width", 2)
    .attr("stroke-dasharray", "7 7");

  svg.append("line")
    .attr("x1", margin)
    .attr("y1", center.y)
    .attr("x2", width - margin)
    .attr("y2", center.y)
    .attr("class", "trig-axis");

  svg.append("line")
    .attr("x1", center.x)
    .attr("y1", margin)
    .attr("x2", center.x)
    .attr("y2", height - margin)
    .attr("class", "trig-axis");

  svg.append("line")
    .attr("x1", center.x)
    .attr("y1", center.y)
    .attr("x2", point.x)
    .attr("y2", point.y)
    .attr("class", "trig-radius");

  svg.append("text")
    .attr("x", radiusLabel.x)
    .attr("y", radiusLabel.y)
    .attr("class", "trig-label radius-label")
    .text("radius");

  svg.append("line")
    .attr("x1", center.x)
    .attr("y1", center.y)
    .attr("x2", projection.x)
    .attr("y2", projection.y)
    .attr("class", "trig-cosine");

  svg.append("text")
    .attr("x", cosineLabel.x)
    .attr("y", cosineLabel.y)
    .attr("class", "trig-label cosine-label")
    .attr("text-anchor", "middle")
    .text("cosine");

  svg.append("line")
    .attr("x1", projection.x)
    .attr("y1", projection.y)
    .attr("x2", point.x)
    .attr("y2", point.y)
    .attr("class", "trig-sine");

  svg.append("text")
    .attr("x", sineLabel.x)
    .attr("y", sineLabel.y)
    .attr("class", "trig-label sine-label")
    .attr("dominant-baseline", "middle")
    .attr("text-anchor", projection.x &gt;= center.x ? "start" : "end")
    .text("sine");

  svg.append("circle")
    .attr("cx", point.x)
    .attr("cy", point.y)
    .attr("r", 6)
    .attr("class", "trig-point");

  svg.append("text")
    .attr("x", width - margin + 8)
    .attr("y", center.y + 5)
    .text("x");

  svg.append("text")
    .attr("x", center.x + 8)
    .attr("y", margin - 12)
    .text("y");

  return svg.node();
}

function clamp(value, min, max) {
  return Math.max(min, Math.min(max, value));
}

What you should be able to do
By the end of this lesson, you should be able to:

identify rows, columns, entries, and matrix shape;
use row-column notation such as \(a_{ij}\);
recognize zero, identity, diagonal, and coefficient matrices;
explain why shape matters before any calculation;
represent small systems or data tables as matrices;
use edumath and SymPy to inspect matrix structure.

What you should be able to do
By the end of this lesson, you should be able to:

interpret a matrix as a function from vectors to vectors;
find the image of a vector under a matrix transformation;
explain why basis vectors determine the whole transformation;
identify common transformations: scaling, reflection, projection, and shear;
connect algebraic matrix products to geometric movement;
use edumath and SymPy to test transformations.

What linear transformations preserve
Linear transformations always preserve:

the zero vector: \(T(\mathbf{0})=\mathbf{0}\);
vector addition;
scalar multiplication;
lines through the origin.

They do not necessarily preserve length, angle, or area. Some do, but many do not.






WarningCommon pitfall



A transformation can be linear even if it changes lengths and angles. Linearity is about preserving addition and scalar multiplication, not about preserving geometry exactly.

What you should be able to do
By the end of this lesson, you should be able to:

add matrices of the same shape;
multiply a matrix by a scalar;
decide whether matrix products are defined;
compute matrix-vector products by row dot products;
read a matrix-vector product as a combination of columns;
verify calculations with edumath, NumPy, and SymPy.

Column-combination view
The same product can be read another way:
\[
\begin{bmatrix}
2 & 1\\
0 & 3
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}4\\5\end{bmatrix}
=4\begin{bmatrix}2\\0\end{bmatrix}
+5\begin{bmatrix}1\\3\end{bmatrix}.
\]
So a matrix-vector product is a linear combination of the columns of the matrix. This idea becomes very important when studying systems and transformations.

What you should be able to do
By the end of this lesson, you should be able to:

explain the equation \(A\mathbf{v}=\lambda\mathbf{v}\) in words;
check whether a proposed vector is an eigenvector;
find eigenvalues of simple diagonal or triangular matrices;
interpret positive, negative, zero, and large eigenvalues;
explain why eigenvectors help with repeated transformations;
use SymPy to compute eigenvalues and eigenvectors exactly.

How to check a proposed eigenvector
To check whether \(\mathbf{v}\) is an eigenvector:

compute \(A\mathbf{v}\);
ask whether the result is a scalar multiple of \(\mathbf{v}\);
if yes, the scalar is the eigenvalue.

Converse and contrapositive
For the statement p -&gt; q:

converse: q -&gt; p;
inverse: not p -&gt; not q;
contrapositive: not q -&gt; not p.

The original implication and the contrapositive are logically equivalent. The converse is not always equivalent.

How to study each lesson
For every worked example, pause and ask:

What type of problem is this?
What feature told me which method to use?
Which algebra step made the expression easier?
How could I check this answer without trusting memory?
What does the final answer mean in words?

A strong study routine is:

read the example once for the story;
copy the solution by hand;
close the solution and redo it;
change one number and try a similar problem;
check with SymPy or edumath only after trying.

Where derivatives may fail
A function may fail to have a derivative at:

a corner, such as \(|x|\) at \(x=0\);
a cusp, where slopes become extremely steep in opposite directions;
a vertical tangent, where slope is undefined;
a discontinuity, where the graph breaks.

Continuity is necessary for differentiability, but continuity alone is not enough. A corner can be continuous but not differentiable.

Vocabulary and notation
The notation
\[
\lim_{x\to a} f(x)=L
\]
means: as \(x\) gets close to \(a\), the output \(f(x)\) gets close to \(L\).
Important words:

approaches: gets close to, not necessarily equals;
target value: the input value \(a\);
limiting value: the output value \(L\);
left-hand limit: approach from values less than \(a\);
right-hand limit: approach from values greater than \(a\).

Vertices and edges
A vertex is a node or object. An edge is a connection between vertices.
Example edge list:
V = {A, B, C, D}
E = {AB, AC, BC, CD}
This graph has four vertices and four edges.

Degree
In an undirected graph, the degree of a vertex is the number of edges incident to it.
For edges AB, AC, BC, CD:

degree of A is 2;
degree of B is 2;
degree of C is 3;
degree of D is 1.


Handshake idea
In an undirected graph, the sum of all degrees equals twice the number of edges, because each edge touches two endpoints.

Worked example 1: Venn regions
Let A={1,2,3}, B={3,4,5}, and universe U={1,2,3,4,5,6}.

only in A: {1,2};
only in B: {4,5};
in both: {3};
in neither: {6}.

Worked example 2: event language
In probability, events are sets. If A is “roll an even number” and B is “roll a number greater than 4” on a six-sided die, then
A = {2,4,6}
B = {5,6}
A intersection B = {6}
The intersection means both events happen.

What you should be able to do
By the end of this lesson, you should be able to:

read vectors as coordinate lists and as arrows in the plane;
add vectors and multiply vectors by scalars;
compute vector length using the distance formula;
compute a dot product;
